<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>come easy to someone • go easy on someone</xh5><p> <i>come easy to someone</i>—<i>(of skills, money, etc.)</i> be mastered or gained easily without much exertion: She has a natural talent for learning, and it <u>comes easy to</u> her. <i>Cf.: easy come, easy go</i>—used to say that smth. you get easily can be lost as easily: Several recessions taught me that unless you are disciplined about saving, money is <u>easy come, easy go</u>.</p><p> <i>go easy on someone</i>—(coll.) be lenient with a person; not treat smb. too harshly: <u>Go easy on</u> Ben: he’s only very young and he tries hard.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>be easy-going</b>—<i>be not easily annoyed or upset by other people’s actions: </i>Mrs. Harris wears the pants at home: Mr. Harris is far too quiet and <u>easy-going</u> to argue with her.</p> </entry>
